INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6c5a3445-ed87-4974-bd6f-d517be30d211',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$AWS IAM — Least Privilege in Practice: Roles, Policies, and Why Root Should Never Touch Production$escape$,
  $escape$Every AWS principal should do exactly one job. Start with AWS managed policies only to understand the shape of permissions, then replace them with customer-managed policies scoped to specific actions and resources. Never attach policies to IAM users — attach them to roles, then let services, Lambda functions, or EC2 instances assume those roles via `sts:AssumeRole`. This eliminates long-lived credentials entirely.

For service-to-service auth, use IAM roles with resource-based trust policies. An ECS task role with `s3:GetObject` on `arn:aws:s3:::my-bucket/prefix/*` is safer than a wildcard `s3:*` on `*`. Use `aws iam simulate-principal-policy` to validate effective permissions before deploying.

Root credentials must have MFA enabled and hardware keys preferred. Create a break-glass IAM user with AdministratorAccess for emergencies — but never use root for daily ops. Use AWS Organizations SCPs to hard-block `sts:AssumeRole` by root across member accounts. Audit with IAM Access Analyzer to surface unused permissions and external resource exposure automatically.$escape$,
  $escape$# Simulate effective permissions before deploying
aws iam simulate-principal-policy \
  --policy-source-arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/my-lambda-role \
  --action-names s3:PutObject s3:DeleteObject \
  --resource-arns arn:aws:s3:::my-bucket/uploads/*

# Find unused permissions in last 90 days
aws iam generate-service-last-accessed-details \
  --arn arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/my-lambda-role

aws iam get-service-last-accessed-details \
  --job-id <job-id> \
  --query 'ServicesLastAccessed[?TotalAuthenticatedEntities==`0`].ServiceName'$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
