INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ed5cdfec-6262-4905-9205-f6a76ac21342',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$AWS High Availability — Multi-AZ Deployments, Failover, and What the SLAs Actually Mean$escape$,
  $escape$AWS Multi-AZ replication separates standby replicas across physically isolated data centers within a region. For RDS Multi-AZ, writes synchronously replicate to the standby before acknowledging — failover triggers automatically within 60–120 seconds via a DNS CNAME flip. This earns a 99.95% SLA vs. 99.9% for Single-AZ deployments.

For EC2, distribute instances across ≥3 AZs in your Auto Scaling Group. Watch out: AZ names (`us-east-1a`) are account-specific mappings — use AZ IDs (`use1-az1`) when coordinating cross-account to ensure you're targeting the same physical zone.

ALB cross-zone load balancing (on by default since 2022) solves AZ skew — without it, an AZ with 2 instances handles the same traffic share as one with 10.

Route 53 failover routing with health checks achieves ~30s cutover when combined with a low TTL. For sub-regional failover, AWS Global Accelerator uses anycast to reroute in under 30s with a 99.99% SLA — bypassing DNS propagation entirely.

RDS failover doesn't change your connection string. Multi-AZ ElastiCache (cluster mode) adds cross-AZ replica promotion with automatic DNS update within seconds.$escape$,
  $escape$aws rds create-db-instance \
  --db-instance-identifier prod-postgres \
  --db-instance-class db.r6g.large \
  --engine postgres \
  --engine-version 15.4 \
  --master-username admin \
  --master-user-password "$DB_PASSWORD" \
  --allocated-storage 100 \
  --multi-az \
  --backup-retention-period 7 \
  --deletion-protection \
  --db-subnet-group-name prod-subnet-group$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
